    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-509">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">If you get any closer to the aerie without summoning mist first, the guards would surely see you.  It's why, as a Bostrat, you were originally chosen to go on this mission.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-510"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-510">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You'll need to SUMMON MIST first, to cloak your descent.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-511"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-511">
    <command xml:space="preserve">summon mist</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-512"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-512">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors to the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-513"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-513">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You tuck in your wings and dive down into the forest below the Aerie, dodging tightly-spaced trees with acrobatic precision.&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-514"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-514">
    <command xml:space="preserve">drop gold</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You haven't got that.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-515"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-515">
    <command xml:space="preserve">i</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You are carrying:&#x000A;  a leather rucksack (being worn, and open)&#x000A;    a purple capsa of opening (closed)&#x000A;    a gold capsa of Down (closed)&#x000A;    a red capsa of hasten (closed)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-516"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-516">
    <command xml:space="preserve">get gold</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Taken.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-517"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-517">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open gold</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You open the gold capsa of Down, revealing a scroll of rudenj.&#x000A;&#x000A;Immediately, "down" now means "towards the gold capsa" instead of "towards the earth".  Even being ready for it, it takes you a few flaps to reorient yourself, and you blink away the slight dizziness.  Then you pause.  No sounds from the Aerie.  Apparently, the new "down" is close enough to the old "down" that whatever sensors they have up there didn't detect a change.  Good.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-518"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-518">
    <command xml:space="preserve">drop capsa</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(the gold capsa of Down)&#x000A;Dropped.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-519"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-519">
    <command xml:space="preserve">u</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You gracefully flit between the trees back up above the canopy.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors to the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-520"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-520">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open purple</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You open the purple capsa of opening, revealing a scroll of rezrov.&#x000A;&#x000A;As you open the purple capsa, an almost-palpable wave of force emanates from it, as the power of the revealed scroll of rezrov is released.&#x000A;&#x000A;The huge double doors to the Great Hall clicks as it unlocks!&#x000A;The magic of the red capsa of hasten prevents it from being opened.&#x000A;The huge double doors to the Great Hall flies open!&#x000A;The straps and buckles on your rucksack fly open and it falls!&#x000A;&#x000A;Dropped.&#x000A;&#x000A;From... well, from everywhere in the Aerie, it seems, Woodpeckers start drumming out messages in their Pounding dialect:  "Intruder!  The enemy is DOWN. Repeat!  The enemy is DOWN."  You realize that creating a gravity well pointing straight at you might not have been the wisest move.&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 1.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-521"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-521">
    <command xml:space="preserve">u</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 2.&#x000A;You've barely left Great Hall Landing Cradle when a squad of Raven Guards wheels in from behind, hot on your tail!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-522"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-522">
    <command xml:space="preserve">d</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors to the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see a leather rucksack (in which are a purple capsa of opening (in which is a scroll of rezrov) and a red capsa of hasten (closed)) here.&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 3.&#x000A;As you dive, you use your knowledge of "true down" to give yourself an edge, pulling around a tree at an angle that should be impossible; diving and twisting through gaps in the  branches that couldn't be done.  Your closest pursuer crashes into a branch, and the others peel off to avoid him.&#x000A;&#x000A;The Raven's frustrated caws echo in the mist, and you plot a now-unseen course returning to the familiar currents above the Aerie.  In time, the woodpeckers cease their drumming, and the cawing fades as well.  Protocol would dictate that they return to guarding priority items, and call up any reserves.&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-416">
    <command xml:space="preserve">n</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">If you get any closer to the aerie without summoning mist first, the guards would surely see you.  It's why, as a Bostrat, you were originally chosen to go on this mission.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-417"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-417">
    <command xml:space="preserve">summon mist</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-418"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-418">
    <command xml:space="preserve">n</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Gardens&#x000A;The royal gardens is the most lavishly opulent and sensuous entrance to any aerie you've seen in your life.  Trees, vines, and flowers of every variety spring up from everywhere, each seemingly placed in it only appropriate spot.  The landing cradle above the Royal Quarters themselves is nestled between gracious arcs of poplar trunks, each bedecked with shaded and inviting roosts.  Which, as you know from your childhood days swooping and laughing through these gardens, invariably contain at least eight guards.&#x000A;&#x000A;From here, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.  The Great Hall is to the south, and the Librum to the southeast.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-419"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-419">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x guards</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">The poplars around the landing cradle contain five guards that you can see (since you know where to look), and almost certainly another five that you cannot (since you know where you can't look).&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-420"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-420">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x cradle</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">The cradle's aesthetics have suffered somewhat from having to be re-grown every time the royal insignia changes, but it's still tastefully lavish.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-421"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-421">
    <command xml:space="preserve">se</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  The Librum Door leads inward to the Librum itself.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters and Gardens.  You can also re-ascend to the skies or descend to the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;A lone Raven guard stands in front of the door, dark eyes shifting as she watches the mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-422"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-422">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x door</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">A canted closed hatch to the Librum, on the east side of the landing cradle.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-423"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-423">
    <command xml:space="preserve">e</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(first opening Librum Door)&#x000A;The guard is entirely too watchful to let you do that.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-424"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-424">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x guard</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">The raven guard wears the well-fitting uniform of the Queen's Guard, complete with a small red insignia on her shoulder.  The silvered knives on her talons are retracted while she stands, and golden razors line her beak.  Oddly, her uniform seems to be covered with... tiny closed padlocks?  That's not the insignia of any order you know.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-425"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-425">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x uniform</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Her uniform consists of loose straps, designed to fit precisely under flagfeathers and provide support while not hampering movement nor flight.  The insignia on her shoulder reads "Ikniq" under an icon of a tongue of fire: the logo of the fire warriors.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-426"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-426">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x ikniq</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Her uniform consists of loose straps, designed to fit precisely under flagfeathers and provide support while not hampering movement nor flight.  The insignia on her shoulder reads "Ikniq" under an icon of a tongue of fire: the logo of the fire warriors.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-427"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-427">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x padlocks</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Yes, those are definitely tiny padlocks, each attached to small leather loops stitched to her uniform.  You peer more intently.  The stitching where the loops attach is definitely newer than the stitching on the rest of the uniform.  They must have been added recently.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-428"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-428">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x knives</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Silvered knives, retracted now, but extendable at will.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-429"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-429">
    <command xml:space="preserve">get knives</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">That seems to belong to the lone guard.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-430"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-430">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open purple</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You open the purple capsa of opening, revealing a scroll of rezrov.&#x000A;&#x000A;As you open the purple capsa, an almost-palpable wave of force emanates from it, as the power of the revealed scroll of rezrov is released.&#x000A;&#x000A;As the shockwave of magic reaches the guard, the padlock on her uniform closest to you pops open.  Then in succession, all the other padlocks she's wearing pop open as well, in perfect concentric circles in order of how distant they are from the scroll.  As her eyes lock with yours, you realize, somewhat belatedly, that you've given her the ability to triangulate on your position.  Without hesitation, she leaps straight at you, before you even have time to let go of the capsa.&#x000A;&#x000A;The door behind her opens silently as she tackles you to the ground.&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;    *** You have been captured. ***&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;Would you like to RESTART, RESTORE a saved game, QUIT, or UNDO the last command?&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-431"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-431">
    <command xml:space="preserve">undo</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;[Previous turn undone.]&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-432"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-432">
    <command xml:space="preserve">w</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".  The huge double doors to the Great Hall are on the west side of the landing cradle, and unguarded.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters and Gardens, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-433"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-433">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x door</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">The huge double doors are canted hatches that lead from the giant landing cradle into the Great Hall itself.  They are adorned with fine scrollwork whose broad swoops and curls branch off into even finer swoops and curls, even down to the level of detail that only a Falcon Clan like yourself could see.  The Throckrian who grew this must have been an archmaster.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-434"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-434">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x doors</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">The huge double doors are canted hatches that lead from the giant landing cradle into the Great Hall itself.  They are adorned with fine scrollwork whose broad swoops and curls branch off into even finer swoops and curls, even down to the level of detail that only a Falcon Clan like yourself could see.  The Throckrian who grew this must have been an archmaster.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-435"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-435">
    <command xml:space="preserve">x cradle</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">The huge double doors are canted hatches that lead from the giant landing cradle into the Great Hall itself.  They are adorned with fine scrollwork whose broad swoops and curls branch off into even finer swoops and curls, even down to the level of detail that only a Falcon Clan like yourself could see.  The Throckrian who grew this must have been an archmaster.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-436">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open red</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(the red capsa of BAR)&#x000A;Before you mess with powerful artifacts from the dawn of civilization, you should probably conceal yourself.  You're a Bostrat; the plan was to summon a mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-437"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-437">
    <command xml:space="preserve">summon mist</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-438"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-438">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open gold</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You open the gold capsa of Down, revealing a scroll of rudenj.&#x000A;&#x000A;From... well, from everywhere in the Aerie, it seems, Woodpeckers start drumming out messages in their Pounding dialect:  "Intruder!  The enemy is DOWN. Repeat!  The enemy is DOWN."  You realize that creating a gravity well pointing straight at you might not have been the wisest move.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-439"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-439">
    <command xml:space="preserve">z</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Time passes.&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 1.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-440"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-440">
    <command xml:space="preserve">z</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Time passes.&#x000A;&#x000A;closeness: 2.&#x000A;A squad of Raven Guards appears, and their war cries exalt as they spot you.  You weave through the air, tumbling and twisting as you try to avoid them.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-441"/>
    </children>
  </item>
