  <item nodeId="node-489">
    <command xml:space="preserve">open purple</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">You open the purple capsa of opening, revealing a scroll of rezrov.&#x000A;&#x000A;As you open the purple capsa, an almost-palpable wave of force emanates from it, as the power of the revealed scroll of rezrov is released.&#x000A;&#x000A;As the shockwave of magic reaches the guard, the padlock on her uniform closest to you pops open.  Then in succession, all the other padlocks she's wearing pop open as well, in perfect concentric circles in order of how distant they are from the scroll.  As her eyes lock with yours, you realize, somewhat belatedly, that you've given her the ability to triangulate on your position.  Without hesitation, she leaps straight at you, before you even have time to let go of the capsa.&#x000A;&#x000A;The door behind her opens silently as she tackles you to the ground.&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;    *** You have been captured. ***&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;&#x000A;Would you like to RESTART, RESTORE a saved game, QUIT, or UNDO the last command?&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-490"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-490">
    <command xml:space="preserve">undo</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;[Previous turn undone.]&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-491"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-491">
    <command xml:space="preserve">showme tiny closed</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">Tiny closed padlocks - thing&#x000A;location: part of the well-fitting uniform worn by the lone guard in Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;unlit, inedible, portable; singular-named, proper-named&#x000A;description: "Yes, those are definitely tiny padlocks, each attached to small leather loops stitched to her uniform.  You peer more intently.  The stitching where the loops attach is definitely newer than the stitching on the rest of the uniform.  They must have been added recently."&#x000A;initial appearance: none&#x000A;printed name: "Tiny closed padlocks"&#x000A;printed plural name: none&#x000A;indefinite article: none&#x000A;list grouping key: none&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve"></commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-210">
    <command xml:space="preserve">test summon</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] d&#x000A;If you get any closer to the aerie without summoning mist first, the guards would surely see you.  It's why, as a Bostrat, you were originally chosen to go on this mission.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] n&#x000A;You'll need to SUMMON MIST first, to cloak your descent.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] summon mist&#x000A;Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;You stop at the natural inflection point for clouds given today's weather.  You could make it thicker still, but it would then start to dissapate.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] d&#x000A;You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[5] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[6] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[7] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] d&#x000A;If you get any closer to the aerie without summoning mist first, the guards would surely see you.  It's why, as a Bostrat, you were originally chosen to go on this mission.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] n&#x000A;You'll need to SUMMON MIST first, to cloak your descent.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] summon mist&#x000A;Calling on your heritage as a Bostrat, you summon moisture from the air, and it slowly coalesces into a creeping grey mist, obscuring you from sight.  In gentler times, you would be doing this to ensure the growth of the fields and forests; now you must use it to hide from prying eyes that would keep you from your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] d&#x000A;You descend in wide circles, pulling mist down with you in what you hope is a sufficiently unsuspicious manner, trusting your memorization of the air currents to tell you where you're going...&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, {other places LS DEBUG}, and as always, you can return to the skies.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[5] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  {LS DEBUG: a few other rooms.  Presumably.  Kitchen, Barracks, Chapel(?), }  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[6] d&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, {other places LS DEBUG}, and as always, you can return to the skies.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[7] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  {LS DEBUG: a few other rooms.  Presumably.  Kitchen, Barracks, Chapel(?), }  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-213"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-213">
    <command xml:space="preserve">test scenery</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] x aerie&#x000A;As you recall, the Royal Aerie was grown and shaped by generations of Throckrites, and now towers over the surrounding forest canopy.  Lush shades of browns and reds, often woven together in intricate patterns or pictures, cover every landing cradle and wall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] x royal quarters&#x000A;As you recall, the Royal Quarters is where the Queen and her family, servants, and certain privileged royalty live.  Every huge common room; every small or large individual apartment is awash in greenery that looks incredibly inviting and imperially homey, and is in reality subtly precisely hostile to the uninvited.  Every roof pitch is too steep; no branch nor ridge is graspable by talons of any size.  The single landing cradle in the middle of the gardens is surrounded by stern and beautiful tree crowns, beset with nooks and crevices for unseen guards and archers: attempting to land there would mean instant death for any but those who belong.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] x librum&#x000A;As you recall, the Librum was your target the last time out, and where you obtained the capsas you brought back with you. Its landing cradle is simply decorated, grown with interlocking redwood and pine in a way that suggests shelves of books.  The reading nooks grown into the sides of the main building proved a reasonable entrance for a creative supplicant; no doubt that method will have been shut down by now.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] x great hall&#x000A;As you recall, the Great Hall is by far the largest building in the Aerie complex, and indeed the largest building you've ever seen in your life.  If the stories are true, its planning took three years, and its growth was overseen by three generations of Throckrites.  Every Royal Throckrite since has sought to put their own personal stamp on the Great Hall, leaving it more than a little haphazardly grown by now, but its current form is still impressive, even as it grows less coherent with every new modification.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] x aerie&#x000A;As you recall, the Royal Aerie was grown and shaped by generations of Throckrites, and now towers over the surrounding forest canopy.  Lush shades of browns and reds, often woven together in intricate patterns or pictures, cover every landing cradle and wall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] x royal quarters&#x000A;As you recall, the Royal Quarters is where the Queen and her family, servants, and certain privileged royalty live.  Every huge common room; every small or large individual apartment is awash in greenery that looks incredibly inviting and imperially homey, and is in reality subtly precisely hostile to the uninvited.  Every roof pitch is too steep; no branch nor ridge is graspable by talons of any size.  The single landing cradle in the middle of the gardens is surrounded by stern and beautiful tree crowns, beset with nooks and crevices for unseen guards and archers: attempting to land there would mean instant death for any but those who belong.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] x librum&#x000A;As you recall, the Librum was your target the last time out, and where you obtained the capsas you brought back with you. Its landing cradle is simply decorated, grown with interlocking redwood and pine in a way that suggests shelves of books.  The reading nooks grown into the sides of the main building proved a reasonable entrance for a creative supplicant; no doubt that method will have been shut down by now.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] x great hall&#x000A;As you recall, the Great Hall is by far the largest building in the Aerie complex, and indeed the largest building you've ever seen in your life.  If the stories are true, its planning took three years, and its growth was overseen by three generations of Throckrites.  Every Royal Throckrite since has sought to put their own personal stamp on the Great Hall, leaving it more than a little haphazardly grown by now, but its current form is still impressive, even as it grows less coherent with every new modification.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</commentary>
    <changed>NO</changed>
    <children>
      <child nodeId="node-214"/>
    </children>
  </item>
  <item nodeId="node-214">
    <command xml:space="preserve">test map</command>
    <result xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] n&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up, down)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[5] e&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  The Librum Door leads inward to the Librum itself.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.  You can also re-ascend to the skies or descend to the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;A lone Raven guard stands in front of the door, dark eyes shifting as she watches the mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[6] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[7] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down towards the Aerie, thrilling to the misty wind streaming through your feathers.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[8] e&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  The Librum Door leads inward to the Librum itself.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.  You can also re-ascend to the skies or descend to the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;A lone Raven guard stands in front of the door, dark eyes shifting as she watches the mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[9] nw&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up, down)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[10] s&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[11] n&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up, down)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[12] se&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  The Librum Door leads inward to the Librum itself.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.  You can also re-ascend to the skies or descend to the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;A lone Raven guard stands in front of the door, dark eyes shifting as she watches the mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[13] w&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[14] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down into the forest below the Aerie, dodging tightly-spaced trees with acrobatic precision.&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[15] u&#x000A;You gracefully flit between the trees back up above the canopy.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[16] e&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  The Librum Door leads inward to the Librum itself.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.  You can also re-ascend to the skies or descend to the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;A lone Raven guard stands in front of the door, dark eyes shifting as she watches the mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[17] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down into the forest below the Aerie, dodging tightly-spaced trees with acrobatic precision.&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[18] e&#x000A;You gracefully flit between the trees back up above the canopy.&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  The Librum Door leads inward to the Librum itself.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.  You can also re-ascend to the skies or descend to the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;A lone Raven guard stands in front of the door, dark eyes shifting as she watches the mist.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[19] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down into the forest below the Aerie, dodging tightly-spaced trees with acrobatic precision.&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[20] n&#x000A;You gracefully flit between the trees back up above the canopy.&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up, down)&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[21] d&#x000A;You tuck in your wings and dive down into the forest below the Aerie, dodging tightly-spaced trees with acrobatic precision.&#x000A;&#x000A;In the Forest&#x000A;The trees below the Royal Aerie grow more closely together than in the rest of the forest, and include a wider variety, so that differently-colored woods could be incorporated into the buildings above.  This makes it harder to navigate down here--or it would if you weren't so amazing at navigation.&#x000A;&#x000A;Even through the mist, your sharp eyes spot a fine net, stretched between the trees.  It seems to be set to prevent anyone from coming up from the forest below.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[22] u&#x000A;You gracefully flit between the trees back up above the canopy.&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, and as always, you can return to the skies or descend to the forest.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;The momentum you had from your dive wears off.  Fun while it lasted!&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[23] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.  Other royal aeries dot the forest in the distance, but this complex holds your quarry.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</result>
    <commentary xml:space="preserve">(Testing.)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[1] d&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, {other places LS DEBUG}, and as always, you can return to the skies.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[2] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  {LS DEBUG: a few other rooms.  Presumably.  Kitchen, Barracks, Chapel(?), }  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[3] n&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[4] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  {LS DEBUG: a few other rooms.  Presumably.  Kitchen, Barracks, Chapel(?), }  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[5] e&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  {Probably be more descriptive here LS DEBUG}.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see Another Important Door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[6] u&#x000A;&#x000A;High Above the Royal Aerie&#x000A;Your summoned mist both obscures you and blocks you from seeing the Royal Aerie.  But you've already memorized its layout, and how it relates to today's air currents, winds, and thermals.  Royal quarters to the north, well defended by circling Raven clan guards.  The librum to the east.  {LS DEBUG: a few other rooms.  Presumably.  Kitchen, Barracks, Chapel(?), }  In the center of the Aerie (and directly below you) is the Great Hall.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[7] d&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, {other places LS DEBUG}, and as always, you can return to the skies.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[8] e&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  {Probably be more descriptive here LS DEBUG}.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see Another Important Door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[9] nw&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[10] s&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, {other places LS DEBUG}, and as always, you can return to the skies.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[11] n&#x000A;&#x000A;Royal Landing Cradle&#x000A;It's dangerous; you can't do anything here yet. LS DEBUG.  (you can go south, southeast, up)&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[12] se&#x000A;&#x000A;Librum Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Librum is beautifully set with interlocking redwood and pine, suggesting shelves of books.  {Probably be more descriptive here LS DEBUG}.&#x000A;&#x000A;To the west is the Great Hall, and to the northwest is the Royal Quarters.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see Another Important Door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;[13] w&#x000A;&#x000A;Great Hall Landing Cradle&#x000A;The Landing Cradle of the Great Hall spreads out over nearly a quarter of the vast building.  During your time here, you learned this was so that when a number of important guests and their retinues arrive at the same time, they can land simultaneously, instead of one after the other, which some would invariably take as meaning "in order of importance".&#x000A;&#x000A;To the north is the Royal Quarters, the Librum to the east, {other places LS DEBUG}, and as always, you can return to the skies.&#x000A;&#x000A;You can see an important door here.&#x000A;&#x000A;&gt;</commentary>
